            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Common Mistake 1: Treating Translation as Localization</h2>
<h3>The Problem</h3>
<p>A utility app entering the Indonesian market translated its English interface directly into Indonesian. User feedback was brutal: "This sounds like machine translation." CTR dropped 40% below expectations, and conversions were even worse.</p>
<h3>Action Steps</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Prioritize native-level translation</strong>: Never rely solely on translation tools or non-native speakers for ad copy</li>
<li><strong>Cultural proofreading</strong>: Have locals read your content and flag unnatural expressions</li>
<li><strong>UI copy adaptation</strong>: Buttons, prompts, and error messages must match local expression habits</li>
<li><strong>A/B test before scaling</strong>: Prepare 2-3 localized versions and test with small budgets before ramping up</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>Indonesian and Malay have subtle differences; Thai involves complex honorifics; Burmese is written left-to-right—these details directly impact user comprehension.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Common Mistake 2: Ignoring Religious and Festival Timing</h2>
<h3>The Problem</h3>
<p>An e-commerce brand pushed alcohol promotions to Indonesian users during Ramadan. The creatives were quickly removed by the platform, and the ad account's权重 was damaged.</p>
<h3>Action Steps</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Build a religious calendar</strong>: Southeast Asia (Indonesia/Malaysia: Muslim; Thailand: Buddhist; Philippines: Christian)</li>
<li><strong>Plan creatives 4-6 weeks ahead</strong>: Adjust strategy before Ramadan, Songkran, Holy Week, Christmas</li>
<li><strong>Mark prohibited categories</strong>: Confirm religious taboos in target markets before launching</li>
<li><strong>Adjust creative tones for festivals</strong>: Use gold/green tones for Ramadan; softer tones for Catholic markets</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2>Common Mistake 3: Missing or Incorrect Payment Configuration</h2>
<h3>The Problem</h3>
<p>An e-commerce site targeting Brazil only offered PayPal and credit cards. 70% of users abandoned at checkout. They later discovered Brazilian users prefer Boleto Bancário and Pix.</p>
<h3>Action Steps</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>SEA essentials</strong>: OVO, DANA, GoPay (Indonesia); Boost, Touch 'n Go (Malaysia); Line Pay (Thailand)</li>
<li><strong>LATAM essentials</strong>: Pix (Brazil), OXXO (Mexico), Mercado Pago (Argentina); card penetration is lower than SEA</li>
<li><strong>Payment page localization</strong>: Payment icons must be clearly visible, not collapsed by default</li>
<li><strong>COD considerations</strong>: Cash on delivery remains popular in Vietnam and Indonesia—confirm with logistics partners</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2>Common Mistake 4: Mismatched Social Platform Selection</h2>
<h3>The Problem</h3>
<p>A team targeted Vietnam with only Facebook and Instagram ads, but their audience was actually young users active on Zalo (Vietnam's local messaging app with 100M+ DAU).</p>
<h3>Action Steps</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Market</th>
<th>Primary Platform</th>
<th>Secondary</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Indonesia</td>
<td>Facebook, Instagram, TikTok</td>
<td>WhatsApp</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Vietnam</td>
<td>Zalo, TikTok, Facebook</td>
<td>Instagram</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Philippines</td>
<td>Facebook, YouTube, TikTok</td>
<td>Twitter</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Brazil</td>
<td>Instagram, TikTok, YouTube</td>
<td>Facebook (30+ users)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Mexico</td>
<td>Facebook, Instagram, YouTube</td>
<td>TikTok (younger)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p>SEA users average 3.5 social platforms daily—recommend multi-platform combos rather than single-targeting.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Common Mistake 5: KOL Collaborations That Miss the Mark</h2>
<h3>The Problem</h3>
<p>A gaming company partnered with a top Chinese gaming streamer for Southeast Asia. The streamer had 5M followers, but conversion rates were near zero. The streamer was unknown in SEA, and the content was in Chinese.</p>
<h3>Action Steps</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Local KOLs &gt; Global KOLs</strong>: Prioritize native influencers, even with smaller followings</li>
<li><strong>Verify audience authenticity</strong>: Fake followers are rampant in SEA—request backend screenshots or third-party verification</li>
<li><strong>Require content localization</strong>: Videos need local-language voiceover or subtitles, not just burned-in text</li>
<li><strong>Test before scaling</strong>: Run 3-5 micro-influencers first, calculate CPA, then decide on larger budgets</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2>Pre-Launch Localization Checklist</h2>
<h3>Creative Compliance</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Text reviewed by native speakers</li>
<li>[ ] No religious taboo elements (pork, alcohol, gambling imagery)</li>
<li>[ ] Character imagery matches local aesthetics (skin tone, dress, facial features)</li>
<li>[ ] No cultural conflicts in imagery, brand logos, or locations shown</li>
</ul>
<h3>Account &amp; Platform</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Confirm platform policies for your product category in target market</li>
<li>[ ] Match account entity with target market (some platforms restrict cross-border accounts)</li>
<li>[ ] Prepare localized landing pages—never redirect to original-language pages</li>
</ul>
<h3>Payment &amp; Conversion</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] At least 2 local payment methods integrated</li>
<li>[ ] Payment page language matches landing page</li>
<li>[ ] Logistics coverage confirmed for all targeting regions (COD requires separate setup)</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<p>Localization isn't "translate and launch." It's a systematic effort spanning language, culture, payment methods, platform selection, and KOL partnerships. While SEA and LATAM offer massive growth potential, users in these markets are highly sensitive to localization quality—your creatives "feeling local" directly determines conversion rates.</p>
